{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_babelfish_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656896/1921022101/0417.xml":{"full_text":"DEMANDS BUDGET\nBILL PASSAGE NOW\ni?\nChamber of Commerce Head\nSees Serious Economic\n1 n?u..\ni waste in rui uier ueiay.\n\nWHY MEASURE IS HELD UP\n\nDefrees Declares Senate, House and\nPresident-Elect Favor\nMeasure.\nPassage with the utmost speed possible\nof the federal budget legislation\nis urged by Joseph II. Defrees. presi,\ndent of the Chamber of Commerce of\nthe United States, in a statement today.\nHe says it is absolutely necessary\nthat' this legislation should be\nenacted at the present session of Con-\ngress to save the people from further\neconomic waste and extravagance. In\nthe interests of economy and efficiency.\nspeaking for the organized\nbusiness men of the country, he calls I\nupon Congress for action?now.\n\"It is only by immediate passage of\nI the hill thmt the country can he assured\nof the benefits of a budget system\nwhen it is so sorely needed,\" said\nMr. Defrees. \"Should a measure so\ngenerally indorsed and which has\ngone through ail the processes of\namendment and. deliberation be permitted\nto remain on the Senate calendar\nfor an entire session without\nbeing taken up for final passage?the\nonly stage that remains?\nBill Called Most ital.\n\"The pending budget bill is the most\nimportant of ihe legislative measures\nnow- in position for passage. It a|ii\nparentis- is not realized what the situation\nis. There is not the slightest\nopposition worthy of note to a budget j\nsystem for the national government\nin either party. In fact, both parties;\nare. committed to it by th?dr plat- i\nforms, and the President-elect lias j\npublicly expressed his desire for this: j\nreform. It is demanded by business\nas a vital part of plans for true j\nnnnnrnv in pnvprnnipnr ornenditures. 1\n\"Delay in this vital matter is plan- j\nBed in order that Congress may make j\nabsolutely certain that two officers i j\nappointed by the President shall be\nremoved only by Congress. These two j\nofficers are given duties which are not\nin fact an absolutely essential part\nof a budget plan, properly speaking. 'J\nPostponement Is Dangerous.\n\"To postpone action until the next I\nCongress meets is a dangerous piece\nof business. The bill will then have\nto be reintroduced and go through all\nthe processes of legislation required\nunder the rules of the House and Senate.\nThis in itself will take time even\nif there were no intentional obstruction\nto the passage of the bill. f\n\"Passage of the bill now can be c\naccomplished without seriously ob- f\nBtructing the passage of appropri-a- 1\ntion bills. Delay is fraught with pos- i\nBibilities of serious consequence.\" 1\ni\nDISCUSS STUDY PLANS.\nc\nMembers of Baron Ferson's Class l\n\nin Healing1 Hold Meeting-. f\nAbout thirty members of Baron Fer- 1\nson's class in healing, which was con-\nducted last winter, met Saturday.}\nevening at the of Mrs. William J\nH. Moses, 2129 Wyoming avenue, to\nconsider means of continuing ^he\nstudy pending the resumption of the e\ndirected work on the return of Baron\nFerson in April.\nThe Saturday evening meetings will i\nbe conducted fortnightly at the same 1\naddress until that event. c\nr\nI\nf Si<u\nm Mann i\n~Jl' You have i\nI/ which you doul\nI us to demonstr;\n?1 expert dry cleai\nprocess.\nA\\ wor^ IS1\nfjP> I!\nIs\nkfe??\nTONG, FAMOUS IN DAYS f\nOF OPIUM DENS, JOINS\nIN WAR ON SMUGGLING\nNEW YORK, February 21.?The\nHip Sing Tong, famous in days\nof secret passageways, opium dens\nand mysterious crimes that were\nprevalent in New York's Chinatown,\nhas joined in a fight against\ndrug smuggling.\nPerhaps no evidence could be *1\nmore convincing that Chinatown,\none-time mecca of the underworld,\nand once symbolic of romance\nand mystery, has changed.\nThe Hip Sing Tong and On Leong\nTong, two factions once engaged\nin deadly warfare, long ago de- B\nclared peace. Now the Hip Sing\nlong\" nas joined xne cunuiwu enemy\nof both factions?law and G\norder. p\nDr. Carleton* Simon, special depntv\npolice commissioner in charge\nof the narcotic squad, attended a c\ndinner of the tong last night. t]\nFour hundred members assured n\nhim they would do all in their\npower to aid in stopping the\nsmuggling of drugs, especially\nopium. o\nsi\nFRIEND OF THE BLIND g\nIS SEEKING HELP HERE 11\nMiss Winifred Holt Wants Aid for\nLighthouses for the Blind\"?Is\nWell Known Writer.\nBlind men and women of Washington\nand their benefactors here are q\ntaking much interest in the work rj\nbeing done here by Jliss Winifred [r\nHolt, wiio Is seeking aid for \"light- a\nhouses for the blind.\" which have\nbeen established in this country anil q\nFrance and which are to be extended 01\nto Italy and Poland. tl\nMiss Holt's work for the blind, as tl\nwriter, speaker an dorganizer, has di\nbeen most extnesive, one of Iter most U\nwidely known books being \"A Beacon ei\nfor the Blind,\" which is the life G\nstory of Henry Fawceit. the sightless st\npostmaster general of England. She tl\nhas several times spoken here in the C\nreading room of the Library of Con- el\ngress. and has expressed the highest\npraise for the work being done there u\nthrough Airs. Gertrude T. Itider, in\ncharge.\nIn her appeal for help for the five\nlighthouses established for the 3,000 c*\nFrench soldiers made blind by the w\nwar. Miss Holt lias received the support\nof Ambassador Jusserand. who JJ\nhas said: \"This work should continue L\nis a monument to the friendship of\nAmerica and France.\" One of the {V\nlargjst Braille printing presses in use J?\nis now run by lighthouse No. 3. in\nParis, and funds are needed so that\nit may continue. Through an error A\nMiss Holt was quoted as saying that <t\nwas the only electric-driven press of q\nts kind. There are, in fact, several\nsuch presses both in this country and\nEurope.\nDR. SHIELDS' Wll I Fll Fn iw\nCM\n3ulk of Estate Devised to Catholic\nSisters' College. fr\nir\nThe will of Rev. T>r. Thomas E. fii\nshields of the Catholic University, b'\nluted December 31. 1020, has been sc\niled for probate. He leaves $3,000 to ir\nlis nephew, Vincent Shields, and a life li\ninnuity of $100 per month to his sec- ct\netary, Frances Askew. The remain- sf\nrig estate is devised to the Catholic <j\nsisters' College, near the university fc\nirounds. of which Dr. Shields was\nlean. a,\nIncluded in the bequest to the col- a\nege are notes abrogating $38,000; g,\nive stock and equipment of college ai\narm, lying between 8th and 12th, Crit- rj\nenden and Varnum streets northeast; jf]\n;ontracts for royalties on books writ- P(\nen by the priest and stock in the v<\nCatholic Education Press. q)\nAttorney Lucien Vandoren and the\nnephew, Vincent Shields, are named\nis executors.\nAn official list of the heroes who fell\nn the great war is being published re\nBy the British government, to be th\nouipletefl in eighty volumes. st\nEHectic\nadards\nlUauGect\nE from the economy of it\n;anty imparted by dry cl\ng, properly done, compel:\niration.\ni suit, a dress, a waist, the f\nit for this early Easter Season.\nite the restorative properties ol\naing at this favorable time.\nratory care alone describes 01\nUnusual delivery service?tl\ndone right in Washington.\nranhattan Gleaning\nand Dyeing Co.\n91 Connecticut Avenue\nRranrka*\nStreet N. W. 3123 14th Street N. 1\n145-147 B Street S. E.\n)p OE Go\nConnect\\\n\nHAN TRIED\nIN LYNCHING CASE\nilabama Sergeant, Accused\nof Murder in Labor War,\nFaces Jury Today.\ny tlii* Associated Press.\nHAMILTON. Ala., .February 21.?\nlien R. Stephens, sergeant in Comany\nM, Alabama National Guard.\n'as placed on trial here today on a\nharge of murder In connection with\nhe lynching of William Baird. a\nliner, near Jasper. Walker county,\nn January 13.\nStephens and eight other members\nf Company M were indicted by a\npecial grand Jury which investiated\nthe execution of the miner. A\nlistrial resulted in the case of Sergt.\n:obert J. Lancaster, the tirst man\n-ied.\nIncident of Coal Strike.\nThe lynching of Baird was an outropping\nof the coal strike war that\nas been waged In the Alabama\nelds since September R. last year,\nhe miner was the ninth man to\nleet violent death in Walker county\n3 a result of the struggle. He was\nring held in prison on a charge\nt Killing James Morris, a private ot\nompany M, immediately after Mors\nhad killed Baird's agred father-intw,\nAdrian Northcutt, a preacher\nnd miner.\nThe lynching of Balrd and subseuent\ninvestigation constituted one\nf the bitterest phases of the strike.\nie latest development in which is\nle controversy between law and or2r\nforces of the state. Sid Cowan,\n>rmer chief deputy in the state lawnforcement\ndepartment. charged\nen. R. E. Steiner. commander of\nate troops, with interfering with\nie' investigation. He also charged\n011 rad W. Austin, chief of the lawiforcement\ndepartment, with issuitr\norder* to \"beat hell out of all\nnion agitators.\"\nMany IS ranches Involved.\nThese charges brought denials anil\n>unter-charges, the ramifications of\nhich involved nearly every branch\nf the military and civil forces of j\nie government. Chief Austin charged j\nlat Cowan and Col. Dallas B. Smith,\noth stationed in Walker county, i\nnew of the existence of a plot to j\nrnch Balrd and failed to report the\niattor. Austin claimed that Cowan\nviild liovo nrni'ont rvrl tliev inrr Vv xr 1\nivulging the alleged plot, which.\nlist in charges, was discovered by\nol. Smith and reported privately to\nowan.\nTWO ASK DAMAGES.\nf. B. E. Co. Defendant in $10,DO\nSuit?$20,000 in Other Action.\nThe Washington Railway and Klee ic\nCompany is named as defendant\ni a suit to recover $10,000 damages\nled in the District Supreme Court j\ny Burlie M. Odum for alleged per-\n>nal injury. Tho plaintilT was riding\ni an automobile which was in col\nsion with a car of the company De- 1\n;mber 21 last. lie says he sustained\nrious injuries. Attorneys Roger\n'Donnel and Octave Bigoness appear\nir the plaintiff.\nA collision between a motor cycle\nad an automobile forms the basis of\nsuit for $20,000 damages tiled by\n?lden O. Babcock against William A.\nid Mattie A. Keckley. Habcoek was\nding the motor cycle May 22 last on\n1 street southwest and sustained\n<gieus injury, he asserts, when the\nihicles came together. Attorneys\nItutt Imlay appear for the plaintiff.\nDR. BAILEY GIVEN D. S. M.\nDr. Pearce Bailey has been awarded\ndistinguished service medal in\ncognition of his services as chief of\ne division of neuro-psychlatry of the\nirgeon general's office.\nut Ave:\nExpress\n7//'//y\" SclX\nV '4 y\nthe^S,\nlean- n\\ Es\n5 ad- Whow\nAre i\nThe C\nitness of _\no? -i. Dupon\nPermit Randa\nf careful, 1 Allan\nI Real\nII Hausl<\nur and\nie Mp?*\nII\n^/i, OKilvi?\nJ/^j ^'n^'?n\nJf jf CookeIf//\nSharp*\nIff Manha\njf I>vei\nS?/ P\nCP\nl?WAriir>n\nicut Avenue Association\nGERMANS DEMA\nOF DYE EXP!\nBetrayal of Comn\nBreach of Contrac\nChemists?Denied t\nIty the Associated Press,\nCOLOGNE, February 20.?Warrants\nhave been issued here for the apprehension\nof four leading1 chemical and\ndye experts formerly employed by\nFriedrich Bayer Co. of Leverskursen,\ncharging them with breach of\ncontract and betrayal of commercial\nsecrets. They are Dr. Joseph Flachslander\nof Oberhausen, Bavaria; Dr.\nHen rich Jordan of Cologne. Dr. Otto\nRunge and Dr. Max Engelmann.\nThe four men are described as old\nand trusted employes. They are\neharged with signing contracts with\nthe du Pont de Nemours Company of\nWilmington. Del., which not only bind\nthem to filter the American company's\nemploy, but also place at its disposal\nother valuable considerations?the\ncumulative benefits of their experience\nwith the Leverskursen concern.\nThey are also charged with \"illegally\nappropriating valuable Tecipes,\nformulae to which they had access\nby virtue of their positions of trust\nand confidence.\nDocument Smuggling Alleged.\nA Dr. Kunze of Zurich, representing\nthe American company, is said to have\nmade the arrangements with the four\nexperts, and it is reported also to\nhave been instrumental in securing\nthe transit across the German-Dutch\nfrontier of a trunk containing important\ndocuments, drawings and\nother scientific material. The Dutch\nauthorities accidentally discovered\nthe trunk, which they seized, and\nordered its return to the prosecuting\n?iuui iit'\\ iii v U11.151U' ujn.ni nit* laiitr m\nrequisition.\nFla-chslander and Run go sailed for\nNew York-011 the steamer llyndam on\nDecember 21. where they were permitted\nto land, although it is declared\nWILL MAINTAIN RELATIONS\nWITH COMRADE NATIONS\n9\nBishop-Elect Manning Says No\nForce San Swerve United States\nFrom That Purpose.\nNEW YORK, February 21.?Rev. Dr.\nWilliam T. Manning, bishop-elect of\nthe Protestant Episcopal iliocese of\nNew Yojk, declared in a sermon here\nthat the people of the United States\nwould allow no force from either\nwithin or without the nation's borders\nto endanger \"our relations with those\nwho were our comrades in the war.\"\n11 a.i /.Vi o/l o t thn tViirt v_\n.air. -IViillJ Ilixift Jiira^utu ai. IUV UI.ILJfirst\nannual church service of the Rons\nof the Revolution iif commemoration\nof the birth of George Washington.\nThe service was held in Trinity\nChurch, where Washington, with the\nVice President and members of Congress,\nattended religious services following\nhis inauguration on April 30,\n17K9. Many other patriotic orders\nwere guests at the service.\nBishop-elect Manning praised the\nwork of the societies in keeping the\nspirit of Washington, Lincoln and\nRoosevelt before the people.\n\"The spirit which stirred our people\nduring the great war is not dead,\" he\nsaid. \"If another call should come\nthey would meet it not less readily,\nhut more readily than before. We all\nknow this is true.\"\nA pearl fisher in Torres straits once\nfound a cluster of pearls in the shape\nof a perfect cross. This cluster, after\npassing through the hands of several\ndealers, was eventually sold to some\nwealthy itoman catholics ior presentation\nto the Pope, the sum paid being\n$50,000.\n\nmie. I\n>edb^i\nyein<f\n?J J\ntablishments\nBusiness Standards\nstrongly Endorsed by\nonnecticu t Avenue\nAssociation\nt National Bank.\nII H. Hagner?Realtor.\nE. Walker Co.?\nttors.\nir Co.?Stationers\nEngravers.\nsternak?Women's Ap'1.\n?Hair Dressing Par?Millinery\nImporter,\nrrado Co.?Interior\n>rators.\nWomen's AppareL\nZ i m m or m an ?-Mi 11 iner.\n?Ladies' Tailor and\norter.\n>hn A. O'Rourke Connor\nDecorators,\ns Sisters?Hair Spests.\ntvood Underwood?\nographers.\nt Cobb?Realtors.\n?Flower Shop.\n;?Men's Tailor,\nttan Cleaning and\nng Co.\ntAyej\nND RETURN\nERTS NOW IN U. S.\naercial Secrets and.\n;t Charged Against\n>y du Pont Employe.\nIthe Dutch authorities demanded their\nreturn on the strength of a warrant\nIssued against them.\nj The whereabouts of Engetmann and\nJordan is unknown.\nHAS FORMULAE IN HEAD.\nFlachslander Denies Smuggling\nDocuments Into Holland.\nWILMINGTON,4 Del February 21.?\nThe du Pont company has declined\n\"fo rthe present\" to comment on the\nissuing of warrants in Cologne, Germany,\nfor the arrest of four chemical\nand dye experts employed by t lie\ndu Pont company on charge oi betraying\ncommercial secrets.\nOf the four chemists named in the\nwarrants, only two have arrived here.\nThey are Dr. Joseph Flachslander and\nDr. Otto Runge.\nDr. Flachslander denied emphatically\nthat any papers or chemical formula\nwere brought to this country by\nhimself or associate. He declared reports\nthat a Dr. Kunze of Zurich had\nsmuggled a trunkfuW of documents\nacross the Dutch frontier were untrue.\nDr. Flachslander asserted he had in\nno way broken faith with his former\nemployer, Friederich Payer\nCo. of Leverskursen. lie declared lie\nregarded the knowledge lie gained in\nthat company's employment as having\nbeen contributed by the research\nwork of himself and his associate\nand that he had brought it all with\nt r?i \"in <1\nThe charge of breach of contract\nDr. Flachslander characterized as\n\"absurd,\" asserting ids contract with\nthe Bayer company expired December\n31 last.\nPRODUCTION MAIN FACTOR\nIN BUSINESS, IS CLAIM\ni\ni\nU. S. Commerce Chamber Review\nDiscloses Prospect of Improved\nConditions in Country.\nProduction is now and will continue\nto be tbe dominant factor in the business\nsituation in the United States\nand business conditions will improve\nfrom the present time on, according\nto the monthly review of business\ncompiled for the Chamber of Commerce\nof the United States by Archer\nWall Douglas, chairman of the chamj\nber's committee on statistics and\nstandards.\n\"Tho most oonvincing evidence that\nwe are on the high road to recovery,\"\nMr. Douglas says, \"is found In the\nuniversal report, brought by traveling\nsalesmen from every section of the\ncountry, of steadily growing sentiment\nthat 'business will be better in\nthe spring'?not a sudden return to\nprosperity, which is neither likely nor\ndesirable, but a slow and natural\nworking out of those processes of\nliquidation, which are now in full\noperation.\n\"All are agreed that the only way\nto hasten matters is by the general\nexercise of the homely virtues of hard\nwork and economy.\n\"While unemployment is still larger,\nthere is more work and less idleness\non the whole in industrial sections.\nThe lessened production in manufacturing\nhas naturally resulted in decreased\noutput of coal. Also in the\noil fields there are falling prices accompanied\nby cutting down the output.\"\n\nT\ny-il\n1 5/ N VIV^<>\nw\nI\nparabl\nand li\nservio\nThe\nI\n\nDISEASE BAFFLING,[\nEDDYLEADERSAYS!\nBicknell Young. Lecturer on:\nChristian Science. Critic\nI\nof Materia! Methods.\nTil a lecture on Ohristf&n Science!\nat the First Church, of Christ. Scientist,\nyesterday afternoon. HlcknellTounvr,\nmember of the board of lectureship\nof the Mother Church at\nBoston, said that, although there have\nbeen many centuries of education in\nthe use of material remedies, diseases\nare not less prevalent, less insistent,\nless fatal, and that they are as mysterious\nand baffling\" as ever to those\nteaching\" and advocating material\nsystems of healing. Vi\n\"Industrial unrest prevails, the high\ncost of living goes on. greed is ranipant.\nin many places crime conditions\nare unchecked, and from a material\noutlook humanity seems to be sailing\na boisterous sea without chart V\nor compass or pilot,\" he added. \"But,\"\nhe said, \"Christian Scientists do not\nj fail to take cognizance of the difiTi- j\ncutties which beset the race as well 1\nas the individual, and they are not\nengaged in any superficial altruistic)\ntheory. j\n\"We claim to have common sense, j m\nand the history of this movement\nshows clearly that, as a closs. Chris- ^r\ntian Scientists are eminently prac- it\nileal.\"\nMr. Young said the Bible is the m\noriginal revelation of the immortal ;ir\nrelationship of God and man. and that i\nj Christian Science makes this rela-\nj tionship understood, and in doing this\nji? removes condemnation and estab- w\ni lishes redemeption in its stead.\nThe lecture was given under the\nauspices of the First Church of Christ.\nScientist, .of this citv. Frank- T _\nBunker introduced Mr. Young-, who!'\nwill be introduced this evening- by 'V\nMrs. Harriett Hitchcock, when the\nlecture will be repeated. The lecture f\nis free to the public. ?r\nPICKS SCHOOL COMMITTEE 1?\nin\nI Chamber of Commerce Gives Per-\nIta\nsqnnel of Selection. th\nt 14\nThe personnel of the new committee\non public schools of the Washington\nChamber of Commerce has been annouuced\nby I'resident Albert Schulteis.\nHenry F. Glassie is named as\nchairman and Arthur Ramsay vice\nchairman. The committee follows: F.\nW. Hallou, F. W. P.olgiano, Charles B.\nCampbell. Charles W. Clagett, Ernest f(\nH. Daniel. Allan Davis. Henrv R. hi\nDavis, Rev. George A. Dougherty, Dr.\nC. R. Dufour